WM: TaijiOS Window Manager

Standalone window manager for TaijiOS. Provides window management
services and the /mnt/wm filesystem.

OVERVIEW

WM provides:

    Window Management    - Create, move, resize, close windows
    Filesystem Interface - /mnt/wm for window control
    Virtual Devices      - Each window has /dev/draw, /dev/mouse, /dev/kbd
    Marrow Integration   - Uses Marrow for graphics rendering

WM is standalone and has no toolkit dependencies.

QUICK START

Start WM (connects to Marrow at tcp!localhost!17010):

    ./bin/wm

Start WM with custom Marrow address:

    ./bin/wm --marrow tcp!192.168.1.100!17010

Start WM and load .kry file:

    ./bin/wm --run myapp.kry

FILESYSTEM

WM exposes /mnt/wm:

    /mnt/wm/
    ├── ctl               - Create top-level window
    ├── win/
    │   └── [id]/         - Window directory
    │       ├── title     - Window title
    │       ├── rect      - "x y width height"
    │       ├── visible   - "1" or "0"
    │       ├── dev/      - Virtual devices
    │       │   ├── draw  - Virtual /dev/draw
    │       │   ├── cons  - Virtual /dev/cons
    │       │   ├── mouse - Virtual /dev/mouse
    │       │   └── kbd   - Virtual /dev/kbd
    │       └── win/      - Nested windows
    └── active            - Symlink to focused window

COMPONENTS

src/main.c           - WM entry point
include/wm.h         - WM client API

BUILD

    mk all              - Build WM binary
    mk clean            - Clean build artifacts

Binary: bin/wm

REQUIREMENTS

    - Marrow (graphics primitives, /dev/draw)
    - TaijiOS Toolkit (window and widget types)
    - Plan 9 C library (lib9)
    - Linux (primary platform)

ARCHITECTURE

WM is standalone:

    wm/           - Window Manager (standalone, no toolkit)
    tk/           - Toolkit (TK only - widgets, layouts)

This separation allows:
    Game libraries (qi) to use WM without loading TK code
    WM to be used with any toolkit
    Better performance (no widget overhead for games)

CONTRIBUTING

Maintain C89/C90 compliance. Follow Plan 9 conventions. Use Plan 9
toolchain (9c/9l) for builds.
